
**What is Network Scanning?**
Network scanning is the process of identifying active devices, open ports, services and vulnerabilities on a network. It helps ehtical 
hackers map the network and understand potential entry points for further testing and exploitaion.

**Important to:**
-> Helps in identifying the attack surface.
-> Assists in security assesments and the audits
-> Critical for penetration testing and defense strategy

**What is Port Scanning?**
Port Scanningis used to discover open, closed or filtered ports on a target system. Is also helps to determine what services 
are running behind those ports.

**Common Port Scan Goals:**
Discover Open ports(e.g; 21-ftp, 22-ssh, 80-http)
Identify services running (e.g; Apache, MySQL)
Detect firewall and filtering rules

**Tools Used:**
NMAP(all in one scanner), NETCAT, MASSCAN, Angry IP Scanner, ARP Scan, fping(fast ping sweep), 
tcpdump(sniff network packets), subnetcalc(calculate subnet mask)
